# Change log comments

When you change project code, add one or more short comments with a **timestamp** and **reason** so future readers can trace why the change was made.

## When to add

- Add comments for every intentional code change you make (not for typo-only fixes in comments/docs unless they clarify behavior).
- Use the date of the change in `YYYY-MM-DD` format.

## Where to put them

| File type | Placement |
|-----------|-----------|
| Most Python modules, templates, etc. | Near the **top of the file**, after encoding/shebang and before imports if possible, or in a dedicated block immediately after imports |
| `systemoversikt/views.py` (and similar large view modules) | Prefer **inside the view (or helper) function** you changed; use a file-top block only when the change spans many views or is global |

Keep new entries **newest first** when using a file-top block.

## Format

Single change (inline or above the changed block):

```python
# 2026-05-27: Exclude archived systems – avoids duplicates in the overview (ticket #1234).
```

File-top block (other modules):

```python
# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
# Change log:
# 2026-05-27: Exclude archived systems – avoids duplicates in the overview.
# 2026-04-10: Added vulnstats cache to reduce Azure API calls.
```

Inside a view function:

```python
@login_required
def system_oversikt(request):
    # 2026-05-27: Sort by last updated – order requested by operations owners.
    ...
```

## Content

- Write change-log comments in **English** by default.
- State **what** changed and **why** (bugfix, requirement, performance, security, user clarification, etc.).
- Reference ticket/issue numbers when the user provides them; do not invent IDs.
- Do not remove older change-log comments unless the user asks to clean them up.
- Use Norwegian only when the surrounding file consistently uses Norwegian for comments and mixing languages would look out of place.
